# UI Design Philosophy

Design for enterprise customers.

Every interface should feel:

- Professional
- Premium
- Clean
- Modern
- Trustworthy

Avoid designs that look like generic templates.

---

# Design Before Coding

Before building a UI:

- Inspect existing sections.
- Identify reusable components.
- Match the existing design language.
- Extend existing patterns before creating new ones.

---

# Layout

Maintain consistent spacing throughout the page.

Keep a clear visual hierarchy.

Avoid clutter.

Prefer balanced whitespace.

Follow existing container widths and alignment.

---

# Hero Sections

Hero sections should:

- Have one clear primary message.
- Include concise supporting copy.
- Use a single primary CTA.
- Keep visual balance between text and media.
- Respect existing MarketingPageHero patterns unless a redesign is requested.

---

# Cards

Cards should feel lightweight and premium.

Reuse existing card styles before creating new ones.

Keep:

- consistent padding
- consistent radius
- consistent border treatment
- subtle hover effects

Avoid oversized cards.

Avoid unnecessary shadows.

---

# Typography

Use existing typography styles.

Maintain clear heading hierarchy.

Avoid long paragraphs.

Keep line lengths readable.

---

# Buttons

Reuse existing button styles.

Maintain consistent spacing around CTAs.

Avoid creating custom button styles unless requested.

---

# Colors

Use existing design tokens.

Reuse CSS variables.

Never introduce random colors.

Respect the project's dark theme.

---

# Icons

Reuse existing icon components.

Keep icon sizing consistent.

Avoid mixing multiple icon styles.

---

# Images

Use high-quality imagery.

Maintain consistent aspect ratios.

Do not stretch or distort images.

Prefer existing asset helpers.

---

# Animations

Animations should enhance usability.

Keep animations subtle.

Use transform and opacity.

Avoid distracting motion.

Respect prefers-reduced-motion.

---

# Responsive Design

Design mobile-first while respecting existing project patterns.

Ensure layouts adapt cleanly across breakpoints.

Never sacrifice readability for aesthetics.

---

# Accessibility

Maintain sufficient color contrast.

Provide meaningful alt text.

Ensure keyboard accessibility where applicable.

Use semantic HTML.

---

# Before Completion

Before finishing any UI work verify:

- Existing components were reused where appropriate.
- Existing design language was preserved.
- Visual hierarchy is clear.
- Spacing is consistent.
- Responsive layout works.
- Accessibility has not regressed.
- No unnecessary visual complexity was introduced.